In the diagram, $PT$ is parallel to $QR.$ What is the measure of $\angle PQR$ in degrees?

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(10,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(10,0),MidArrow);
draw((10,0)--(20,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(-7,10)--(7,10)--(10,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((-5,10)--(7,10),MidArrow);
label("$x^{\circ}$",(-6,10),SE);
label("$2x^{\circ}$",(7,10),SW);
label("$128^{\circ}$",(10,0),NE);
label("$P$",(-7,10),N);
label("$T$",(7,10),N);
label("$R$",(10,0),S);
label("$Q$",(0,0),S);
[/asy]
# known:
1. **Angles on a line / linear pair**: If two rays form a straight line, the adjacent angles form a linear pair and are supplementary: their measures add to \(180^\circ\).
2. **Parallel lines & corresponding/alternate angles**: When a transversal crosses parallel lines, corresponding or alternate interior angles are equal. Use this to relate an angle at the top parallel line to the given angle at the bottom line.
3. **Angles around a point**: Angles that share a vertex and fill a straight line can be expressed as sums of smaller angles; often you equate a labeled angle (like \(2x^\circ\)) to a known angle using parallel-line angle relationships.
# Answer:

ref_solution:
Since $PT$ and $RQ$ are parallel, then $2x^\circ=128^\circ,$ so $x=64,$ so $\angle TPQ=64^\circ.$

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(10,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(10,0),MidArrow);
draw((10,0)--(20,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(-7,10)--(7,10)--(10,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((-5,10)--(7,10),MidArrow);
label("$x^{\circ}$",(-6,10),SE);
label("$2x^{\circ}$",(7,10),SW);
label("$128^{\circ}$",(10,0),NE);
label("$P$",(-7,10),N);
label("$T$",(7,10),N);
label("$R$",(10,0),S);
label("$Q$",(0,0),S);
[/asy]

Since $PT$ and $QR$ are parallel, then $\angle TPQ$ and $\angle PQR$ are supplementary. Thus, $\angle PQR + 64^\circ = 180^\circ,$ so $\angle PQR = \boxed{116} \text{ degrees}.$

